'''Paul Geraghty''' (born 3 May 1959, in [[Durban]], [[South Africa]]) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] based [[author]] and [[illustrator]] of children's [[picture books]]. He also writes [[teenage]] [[fiction]] and won the Young Africa Award for his first novel ''[[Pig]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url= http://openlibrary.org/b/OL2272010M/Pig|title=Pig by Paul Geraghty |accessdate= 5 March 2010 |publisher=Open Library }}</ref>

== Background ==

He read ''[[Fine Arts and English]]'' at [[Natal University]], South Africa and holds a Higher Diploma in Education. After teaching for two years in [[Cape Town]] he took a [[copywriter]]<U+2019>s job in advertising. There he met [[John Bush]], who would later go on to collaborate with him on three picture books. Since 1986 he has lived in [[London]], UK.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.buckscc.gov.uk/bcc/libraries/children/paul_geraghty.page |title=Paul Geraghty |accessdate=6 March 2010 |publisher=Buckinghamshire County Council }}</ref>

Geraghty<U+2019>s picture books typically centre on wildlife/environmental themes, either treated in a highly realistic manner, rich in detail, or irreverently stylised, usually illustrated in watercolour.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.childrensdiscovery.org.uk/author-profiles/our-authors/new-page/ |title=Paul Geraghty |accessdate= 5 March 2010|publisher=Children's Discovery Centre }}</ref> Translated into over 20 languages internationally, his work has won various awards, including the [[Children's Book Award]] for Solo in 1996.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.redhousechildrensbookaward.co.uk/past-winners-1990-1999.html |title=Past winners from 1990-1999 |accessdate=5 March 2010 |publisher= Red House Children's Book Award}}</ref>

A frequent lecturer and live illustrator on the literary circuit, he is renowned for his inspirational, if eccentric style with audiences of all ages.

He is a [[musician]], [[photographer]] and extensive traveller.

